questions.query: How does your project contribute to the advancement of the Web3 grants ecosystem?
questions.explanation: Development of Web3 Grants tooling, Aggregation of Web3 grants news and events, Contributions to Web3 grants on-chain registry

questions.query: Describe your previous work or plans related to the Web3 grants ecosystem.
questions.explanation:
Apart from our main platform and metrics around Layer 2 chains, we are building public goods funding trackers. 

Our best known is the RetroPGF3 tracker. Also, we are building and maintaining the Octant Epochs tracker. 

Also, we are labelling smart contracts in the Ethereum scaling solution space to make smart contracts more transparent and tie them to projects. For this, we are also contributing to the Open Source Observer's database on project tagging.

questions.query: How does your project create value for the Web3 grants ecosystem?
questions.explanation: As previously described, it makes projects, their achievements, their funding sources and work transparent, by visualizing data, labelling their contracts and tying them to other data sources.

questions.query: Describe your team's expertise in your chosen focus area within Web3 grants. Include relevant experience, publications, or past projects.
questions.explanation: We are a skilled team to build maintain the platform, in this case more importantly researcher, data analysts as well as design and frontend development.

questions.query: How do you plan to share insights, methodologies, or tools developed through your project with the Cartographer Syndicate and the broader Web3 grants community?
questions.explanation:
We will continue the work in labelling and making the trackers more accessible on our platform as well as social media. 

For example, we are planning to highlight certain projects, grant and funding rounds on our landing page much more for visibility of different opportunities for builders. Oftentimes, builders do not see how they can get funding for their projects but use our data to find options and also where to build what.

questions.query: Describe your previous work or plans related to the Arbitrum ecosystem. How does your project strengthen Arbitrum's foundational infrastructure, improve developer efficiency, or accelerate the adoption of novel applications?

questions.query: Please describe how your project contributes to the growth and development of the Octant ecosystem.
questions.explanation: We built an Octant tracker, we are also regularly posting about Octant and participating projects on our social media channels (X, Farcaster, Lens).

questions.query: How does your project align with the round's focus on community and education within the Octant ecosystem?
questions.explanation: Our platform exists to bring transparency to the Ethereum ecosystem, for free and as a public good. We show visualizations what's happening on different Layer 2s, for end users and for builders. We also educate people about interpreting data, and provide knowledge around Layer 2s in our docs or on social media.

questions.query: Provide a clear roadmap of your project, detailing future milestones and deliverables. How does this demonstrate your commitment to long-term impact and growth within the Octant ecosystem?
questions.explanation:
Future milestones:
* Realtime data summary page
* More chains listed, especially the goal is to list all active Superchain chains
* Application view: Which apps are running on which Layer 2s/3s? - we achieve this by continuously labeling smart contracts and identifying them. (Also see our work on OLI (Open Labels Initiative) and what we do for the Open Source Observer).
* More Builder focus - help them understand the space and where to launch best - by making informed decisions based on data.

questions.query: Describe your team's expertise and how it contributes to the successful execution of your project.
questions.explanation: See project description. We are 8 people and built growthepie from scratch since February 2023.

questions.query: How does your project complement or enhance existing initiatives within the Octant ecosystem rather than competing directly against them?
questions.explanation: We provide an independent data view - as an extension to our core work on data and visualizations for Layer 2s, we show builders that funding in the public goods space is very much possible, by designing trackers amongst other things.

questions.query: Describe your approach to community engagement and how you plan to contribute to a collaborative and constructive funding environment.
questions.explanation: We are not VC funded and want to show that a platform built entirely based on public goods funding as a business model is sustainable. Octant is very much part of this. For this, we also grow our social channels to have the reach to provide data and knowledge around these topics to a broad range of people.

questions.query: How do you plan to use the funding to maximize your project's ongoing impact within the Octant ecosystem if selected?
questions.explanation:
* Pay for infrastructure and upgrading the platform
* Salary for the team (based in EU and US)

questions.query: What unique educational content or resources have you created for the Octant ecosystem? How has the community received these? Please share any relevant links
questions.explanation:
See above, the Octant tracker and posts on Social media: https://www.growthepie.xyz/trackers/octant
We are currently working on a new Octant tracker for which the first version is due in the next week.

data.title: Optimism - Cycle 14 grant
data.description:
How do you justify the size of the request?: 

With our first and only grant so far from the Ethereum Foundation, we demonstrated we can deliver on important milestones and create a user-friendly product that is accessible also to beginners in the web3 ecosystem. We have many people on the team ensuring thorough testing and tweaking of our platforms features so that everything feels smooth to the end user. User-centred UX Design is an important part of this as well as research on what we can add to meet our user’s needs. The core of our product is that users have access to data and can learn about events in the Layer 2 ecosystem in an easy-to-understand way, always having up-to-date and reliable data visualised and in their hands.

We have not taken any paid-for measures and do not plan to do this. We want to keep this platform as a public good (fully open-sourced backend and frontend with openly accessible API endpoints).

We will use the grant to:

provide a reliable infrastructure and to aggregate data: The grant will help to cover infrastructure costs (AWS, RPC providers, etc.) and the team including data analytics and backend development.

design and maintain a well-tested platform with a smooth user experience and cover team cost for design and frontend implementation.

create content that is targeted at beginners to intermediates, with this grant specifically for developers of the OP Stack code base. Creating easy-to-consume educational content and programmes takes time to develop, hence a lot of time will be needed to draft, test, and iterate the content for our user group.

to provide a Spanish localization of educational developer content. Roadmap

Describe in discrete steps your plan for accomplishing your project:

After the release of our general Blockspace category, we will research and aggregate data for a selection of OP Stack projects. Either through sourcing data from RPCs or running our own nodes.

Design of a labelled area for OP Stack chains based on our Blockspace UX, also providing the possibility to better compare the chains’ activities.

Implementation of 3 OP Stack chains as a start.

Launch of initials metrics and additional metrics for the 3 selected projects (transaction costs, transaction count, tvl, daily active users, stablecoin market cap, fees paid, rent paid to L1, profit margin) providing the ability to compare these with other Layer-2s through our standard metrics pages and single chain pages.

Educational content creation and resource collection for these 3 selected projects

Labelling of OP stack chain smart contracts, testing and launch of the OP Stack Blockspace area with first educational content and metrics including end-user and developer wiki (glossary, vision of different L2s, etc.).

Localization of the whole page for the Spanish speaking community, especially for Spanish-speaking developers.

On a regular basis for the coming months, more projects based on the OP Stack code base will be added.
